Originally reported on Google Code with ID 1242 What version of AnkiDroid are you using? AnkiDroid v2.0beta6
On what version of Android? 2.2 and 4.1 (emulator)
Any elements that have been given a font-size style do not scale if using "em" as the unit. E.g,. .card { font-size: 2em; }
On the desktop client, the fonts in the card are scaled accordingly. On AnkiDroid, they do not scale. Changing the "Relative font size" has no effect on the text size, whether it's 10% or 150%.
Using pixels instead does indeed scale the text. I.e., the following does get scaled: .card { font-size: 25px; }
The issue is present in cards where the usage of px and em is intermixed among different elements, where those that use px are scaled, and those that use em are not. Reported by Houssam.Salem.Au on 2012-07-21 05:43:18

Originally reported on Google Code with ID 1361 Right now JavaScript resizes big images so that they fit on the screen, with the size given by this piece of Java:
mCardTemplate = mCardTemplate.replaceFirst("var availableWidth = \\d*;", String.format(Locale.US, "var availableWidth = %d;", getAvailableWidthInCard()));
Apparently this can be done in a much easier way, with no JavaScript:
webview.getSettings().setLayoutAlgorithm(LayoutAlgorithm.SINGLE_COLUMN);
See http://stackoverflow.com/a/12327010/226958
Having no JavaScript might also make card loading a bit faster. Reported by nicolas.raoul on 2012-09-08 05:01:03

